**The affirmative will argue that they resolve a particular instance of international insecurity; however, the causes of wars run deeper – particular events and threats flow on a deeper bed-rock of strategic reason and sovereignty. These dual ontologies render conflict unavoidable and necessary since all life becomes usable for geostrategic ends.**
<span style="line-height: 15px;">__<span style="font-size: 10.5pt;">Burke</span>__ <span style="font-size: 8.5pt;">, senior lecturer at University of New South Whales, </span> __<span style="font-size: 10.5pt;">07 </span>__ <span style="font-size: 8.5pt;">[Anthony, “Ontologies of War: Violence, Existence and Reason”, theory & Event, 10, 2]</span></span>


**The impetus toward security is premised on an ontological framework that commits itself to order and control not only of conflict, but of life itself. This drive to order anything and everything guarantees that the mass graves and nuclear holocausts of the 20th century will be repeated.**
__<span style="font-family: Georgia; font-size: 10.5pt;">Burke</span>__<span style="font-family: Georgia; font-size: 8.5pt;">, senior lecturer at University of New South Whales, </span>__<span style="font-family: Georgia; font-size: 10.5pt;">07 </span>__<span style="font-family: Georgia; font-size: 8.5pt;">[Anthony, “Ontologies of War: Violence, Existence and Reason”, theory & Event, 10, 2] </span>


**<span class="TagsChar">Were they to succeed, the measures of security championed by the affirmative would manage to protect life only by suppressing some profoundly valuable part of it. Difference, Uncertainty, and Change are important parts of what makes life beautiful. Security is a hostile effort to eradicate these paradoxes in favor of knowledge and predictability. This results in resentment toward a domesticated life hardly worth living. </span>**
<span style="line-height: 15px;">**__<span style="font-size: 10.5pt;">Der Derian</span>__****<span style="font-size: 8.5pt;">, Professor of IR and political science at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, </span>****__<span style="font-size: 10.5pt;">in </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10.5pt;">ʻ93 </span>__****<span style="font-size: 8.5pt;">[James, , “The Value of Security: Hobbes, Marx, Nietzsche and Baudrillard”, The Political Subject of Violence, ed.David Campbell and Michael Dillon, Page 101-105]</span>**</span>


**Our alternative is to renounce the affirmativeʼs violent and futile search for security in favor of affirming an insecure life. Precisely the defining characteristic of human being is its vulnerability to Otherness. Rather than responding to this with a fear that calcifies into a defensive disposition against difference, we should celebrate our condition in order to seek outan ethical politics of work on the Self. This model of responsibility is the only ontologically appropriate response to the dangers that we inevitably face, whereas the administrative politics of the affirmative damn us to race from one threatening scenario to another, militarizing all ofbeing in a fruitless search for sovereignty and certainty.**
<span style="line-height: 15px;">**__<span style="font-size: 10.5pt;">Dillon</span>__****<span style="font-size: 8.5pt;">, professor of politics and international relations at University of Lancaster, </span>****__<span style="font-size: 10.5pt;">in ʻ96 </span>__****<span style="font-size: 8.5pt;">[Michael, The Politics of Security: Toward a Political Science of Continental Philosophy, pg. 137-143]</span>**</span>


**Our alternative refuses security in favor of a work on the Self which celebrates difference and questions international relationsʼ impetus toward sovereignty and sameness. Such a move is capable or radically resituating politics from the ground up and or creating ethical relationships with an insecure world.**
